In a traditional Italian-American neighborhood (called Arthur Avenue) near Fordham University and The Bronx Zoo in The Bronx, NY, is an old school Italian restaurant that serves from a menu that is only proudly recited by the waiters, often with delightfully wry Bronx humor.  There will be an array of chef's choices offered as specials -- but of course if you have a favorite meal, you can always ask.  The wine is served in unpretentious little wine glasses and you or your group may be seated on one of two floors at long tables.  On busy days, the din of multi-generational groups (it's kid noises friendly), tourists and neighbors lends it a sparky, lively, cafe atmosphere where everyone seems to have a smile for the groups at the next tables.  If you prefer a quieter or romantic outing, try to stop by on a weekday or when weather is colder.  (Over 30 years, I have occasionally seen lines running out the door and up the block on weekends, since many urban insiders know it's well  worth it. )  Three of us spent $150 for everything (wine) but dessert.  We ordered appetizers to chow on with the bread that's brought to the table and a simple leafy green salad.  Entrees included perfectly tender calimari in a marinara,  plump meatballs and fresh linguine and a somewhat complex bolognese sauce on pasta -- and all in generous portions.  (Be sure to bring cash). After dinner at Dominick's, you'll want to stop by Gino's Bakery to stock up on everything from sesame almond biscotti to layered pastries that are inscribed in frosting on the top -- 'Chaz'.  This is one of the pastries that has been a favorite of Gino's most famous (almost most famous?) customers, Chaz Palmieri, and several are often reserved for his visit later in the afternoon.  We ran into Mr. Palmieri, screenwriter (A Bronx Tale) and actor, at the dizzyingly abundant green market across the street.  We didn't want to bother him, but snapped a quick photo.  Every visit to Arthur Avenue is an adventure of a new kind (we often get fresh pasta or a crusty fresh-baked bread, mascarpone and fennel -- or we'll pick out gifts that might include imported Italian sausages, prosciutto and cheeses.)  This is a daytrip that still offers an authentic New York neighborhood experience that will make your heart sing.  Oh, street parking, as you might guess,  is in demand but we have always found a spot so far, some days closer than others.  Be sure to bring cash.

Iconic, delicious,  a must eat there are 3 simple terms that describe Dominicks. This place is NOT for the impatient diner nor for those who no longer use cash. When you walk in you are given a number and directed to the upstairs bar. We had a Chianti Riserva while we waited for the bartender to announce our number. The dining room, has communal tables that seat 8, and we dined with a delightful family from New Jersey. We started with the stuffed artichoke that was baked until tender.  There are not menus, for those first timers, the waiters will tell you the special as well as the complete offerings from the kitchen. Servings are not for the light eater, we had the Stuffed Calamari which was cooked perfectly with a chopped shrimp and clam stuffing served over rice. The Veal Parmigiana was served over pasta. The 2 veal cutlets were thick pieces of veal perfectly seasoned and topped with mozzarella cheese. The Chicken Scarpariello could have served my entire party. 8 perfectly cooked pieces of dark meat chicken on the bone with a hint of spice that made the dish addicting. Dominicks is a must go to when visiting the New York Metro area.

One of the most deceptive things about looking over google ratings is the expectation that a restaurants rating is scaled accurately to its quality. Last time I checked Dominick’s had something like a 4.3 out of five stars, but if it was rated accurately, it would go off the scale and be at 10 stars. Folks, if you’re looking for New York authenticity this is the place. The food is unique and exceptional. The portions are generous, the recipes original and delicious, the atmosphere has that peculiar fusion of NY hospitality and grit. It’s hands down the best Italian restaurant in NYC for its complete value, don’t eat anyplace else in the Bronx or Arthur Ave save for Tra Di Noi. Dominick’s has community tables which is the only legitimate knock I’ve ever heard about it for people who are by the book civil libertarians and don’t want any surveillance, but it’s also a ridiculous thing to care about when the food is giving you one of the most exhilarating experiences of your culinary life. Here the linguine Calamari is delectable, not rubbery like over at Pasquale’s. And you know I’m telling the truth when I say that because supposedly the guy is with the mafia so hopefully he’s not reading this right now.

Dominick's is an iconic Italian restaurant.  Located on Arthur Avenue in the Bronx.   Long tables which are good for groups.   You can order family style or individual plates.   No menu,  they just tell you what they have.  No fish on Sunday's.   Chicken Scarpiello, sausage,  and meatballs are highly recommended.   Ziti, Lasagna,  and Cavatelli are great pastas.  Moderately clean facilities.   Public Restrooms are upstairs.   Staff is good.   CASH ONLY!!!!  We will definitely be going back.
The food was delicious! A little tight in the dinning room, and they don't have high chairs, but you can't beat the food.
Great food at a reasonable price.

I have never been so disappointed at a restaurant before.  I have eaten at Dominick's many times, yesterday was a disaster.  Uncaring waiters, poorly produced meals. The chicken was not browned, it was served with nothing but a lot of boiled potatoes that had sauce poured over them.  It was the first time only the downstairs dining room was used.  As we always do we went next door for coffee and desert.  There were a lot of people there that had eaten at Dominick's they all had the same opinion that it has gone down hill!!!  I will never go back!
